{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501553"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:29:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:29:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1764"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1764"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.2,0.02,0.12,0.55]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1764"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48994"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1764"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1764"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34008"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"914"},{"type":"tags","id":"1243"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8969"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10249"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10275"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42393"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48994"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man brought into the Emergency Department following a motor vehicle crash in which he was thrown from his motor cycle. He is able to provide details of the event. Initial assessment reveals a patent airway. He is saturating at 98% on room air, respiratory rate is 18/min, blood pressure 100/90mmHg, and pulse rate 84/min. His pupils are equal and reactive. Glasgow Coma Scale is 15. Initial arterial blood gas and ECG are unremarkable. A chest X-ray is performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe complains of severe pain over his right scapula and is unable to move his right arm without significant discomfort. On examination, there is visible swelling and bruising over the right scapula. The patient is guarding his right shoulder, and there is localised tenderness over the scapular region. He has limited active and passive range of motion in his right shoulder.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate managment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Surgical fixation with plates and screws","Closed reduction with immobilisation.","Immediate physiotherapy and range of motion exercises.","Observation and conservative management without immobilisation.","Application of a shoulder sling for immobilisation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EScapular fractures, especially those that are not significantly displaced or associated with severe instability, are often managed conservatively with \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmobilisation\u003C/strong\u003E using a shoulder sling. The purpose of immobilisation is to allow the fracture to heal while minimising pain and discomfort.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical fixation with plates and screws:\u003C/strong\u003E Surgical fixation is typically reserved for specific cases, such as severely displaced scapular fractures or fractures associated with significant instability. Intra-articular extension into the glenoid is also a significant indication for surgical intervention in scapula fractures, given the potential impact on shoulder joint function and stability. In the given case, there is no mention of significant displacement or instability, so immediate surgery is not the first-line treatment. Conservative management is usually preferred unless there are compelling reasons for surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClosed reduction with immobilisation\u003C/strong\u003E: Closed reduction is a procedure to realign displaced bone fragments. Scapular fractures are often managed conservatively with immobilization using a shoulder sling rather than closed reduction, especially in cases where the fracture is not significantly displaced. Closed reduction might be considered if there were significant displacement, but this is not indicated in the scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate physiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E and range of motion exercises: In the acute phase of a scapular fracture, physical therapy and range of motion exercises are generally contraindicated. The primary goal in the early stages of management is to provide rest and support to the fractured scapula. Physical therapy and range of motion exercises are typically initiated in the later stages of recovery once the fracture has healed and the patient is cleared by a healthcare provider.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation and conservative management \u003C/strong\u003Ewithout immobilisation: Conservative management without immobilisation may lead to increased pain and discomfort for the patient. Immobilisation with a shoulder sling is commonly employed in scapular fractures to provide support, reduce pain, and facilitate healing. Failing to immobilise the shoulder can result in complications and hinder the healing process.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Minimally displaced fractures, which account for more than 90% of scapular fractures, management is with short-term immobilisation in a sling and swath"],"references":["Libby C, Frane N, Bentley TP. Scapula Fracture. [Updated 2023 Jul 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537312/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34008"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1764"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20058"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20058"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/06767e3f-825e-4b28-b5c5-8cd183de30b8.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/06767e3f-825e-4b28-b5c5-8cd183de30b8.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":554,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34008"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-21T20:22:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-21T20:22:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1764"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48994"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of the